This is an array of objects without being an array.  There's nothing to reliably split on here.  I can't rely on `\n` since some of the output is formatted.  I also can't rely on buffering as the parsing the output becomes heavily dependent on both the Python buffering and the buffering that happens when reading `stdout`.  Convention in the HTTP space is to include a `\n\n` as a means of denoting a break.

This is streamed out and does not provide any context for what is about to happen.  After reading the first  line I can interpret that I'm about to fetch ~500kb of information, but I don't know what's happening after that.  I don't know how many packages are going to fetched or linked until the very end.

This should start with a pre-amble that tells me what's about to happen, then stream the results with a separator.

### Description
The current data store API seems to be inspired by Java and does not feel very pythonic. A simple `dict` access would better suit python code.

Implementation in getgauge/python.py can be:
```python
class DataStoreContainer:
    def __init__(self):
        self.__scenario = dict()
        self.__spec = dict()
        self.__suit = dict()

    @property
    def scenario(self):
        return self.__scenario

    @property
    def spec(self):
        return self.__spec

    @property
    def suit(self):
        return self.__suit


data_store = DataStoreContainer()
```

It can be used in step as follows:
```python
from getgauge import step, data_store

@step("description")
def step_fn():
	value = data_store.scenario['key']
```

This API can also be made backwards compatible through existing `DataStoreFactory` interface.

I can query the schema with simple queries, but I can't figure out how to pass variables using the API.

E.g., if I have the following payload from my Relay client:

REQ = {
  "query": "query User($userId_0:ID!) {\n  user(userId:$userId_0) {\n    id,\n    ...F0\n  }\n}\nfragment F0 on User {\n  id,\n  title\n}", 
  "variables": {
    "userId_0": "VXNlcjpVLTE="
  }
}

My query works fine with GraphiQL. And schema.execute(query) works if I manually input the query params (i.e., userId) into the query string. I was expecting execute to have a "variables" param?

I'm not 100% sure if this is the right way to use this method, but when I use the otThreadDiscover method with the EUI64 and joinable filters enabled to discover joinable networks. I don't get any response. But I can join the network using the otJoinerStart method.

When I look to the difference of this two methods I see that the otJoinerStart method encrypt the EUI64 before comparing this to the discover results with ot::MeshCoP::ComputeJoinerId.

I have fixed this problem with the following:
